## 4. Important Things to Know

### **Two Very Different Stores, Two Different Philosophies:**

**Apple App Store:**
- **Stricter rules**: Human reviewers test every app thoroughly
- **Expensive**: $149/year ongoing cost
- **Faster reviews**: Usually 24-48 hours
- **Unique requirement**: Must offer "Sign in with Apple" if you offer any third-party login
- **Higher bar**: Expects polished, native-feeling apps
- **Appeal process**: Can dispute rejections with detailed explanations

**Google Play Store:**
- **More lenient**: Mix of automated and human review
- **Cheaper**: $25 one-time fee
- **Slower initial review**: 3-7 days for first submission
- **Flexible testing**: Offers multiple release tracks (Internal → Closed → Open → Production)
- **Detailed data disclosure**: Data Safety form is very comprehensive
- **Gradual rollout**: Can release to 5%, 10%, 25%, 50%, 100% of users incrementally

### **The "Sign in with Apple" Requirement:**

This is critical for iOS:
- If your app offers **any** third-party login (like Microsoft, Google, Facebook), Apple **requires** you to also offer "Sign in with Apple"
- Failure to include this is one of the most common rejection reasons
- It must be equally prominent to other login options
- This is non-negotiable—Apple enforces this strictly

**Why?** Apple wants to give users a privacy-focused option that doesn't share their data with third parties.

### **AI Disclosure Requirements (2025 onwards):**

Both stores now require clear labeling of AI-generated content:
- Must indicate when responses are from AI (not human experts)
- Can't misrepresent AI as professional financial advice
- Must include disclaimers like: "Walter is an AI assistant. Quotes are indicative only and not professional advice. Please verify with a licensed broker."

### **Privacy is Paramount:**

Both stores treat privacy as the #1 priority:
- **Privacy policy must be public** (not behind a login)
- **Must accurately declare all data collection** (if you collect emails but don't declare it, instant rejection)
- **Must explain why you collect data** (not just what)
- **Must offer data deletion** (users can request their data be removed)
- **Microphone access requires explanation** (iOS popup text, Android permission justification)

### **The Testing Phase is Essential:**

Before submitting:
- Test on **real devices** (not just simulators/emulators)
- Test on **multiple screen sizes** (small phones, large phones, tablets)
- Test **edge cases**: No internet, denied microphone permission, expired login tokens
- Have **non-technical people test it** (if you can't figure out how to use it, reviewers will reject it)
- Ensure **zero crashes** (even one crash during review = rejection)

### **Demo Accounts Save Time:**

Both stores require you to provide test credentials if the app needs login:
- Create a dedicated `reviewer@waltervoice.com` account
- Pre-populate it with sample data (quotes, chat history)
- Include the credentials in the "Review Notes" section
- Don't delete or change this account during review
- Keep it active even after approval (for future update reviews)

### **Timeline Expectations:**

The document estimates **6-10 weeks total**, but this assumes:
- You already have a finished, tested app
- You have all legal documents ready
- You have business verification documents
- Nothing goes wrong

**Reality checks:**
- First submissions almost always get rejected at least once
- D-U-N-S number can take full 10 business days (Apple can't speed this up)
- If you're new to app development, add 2-4 weeks for learning curve
- If reviewers have questions, each response can add 1-3 days

### **Costs Beyond the Obvious:**

The document lists $149 AUD + $25 USD for store accounts, but hidden costs include:
- **Designer time**: Creating professional screenshots, app icons, feature graphics (or hiring someone: $200-$1000)
- **Legal review**: Having a lawyer review your privacy policy and terms ($500-$2000)
- **Testing devices**: If you don't own iPhones and Android phones (or borrowing from friends)
- **EAS Build costs**: Expo's cloud build service has usage limits (may need paid plan for many builds)
- **Optional costs**: App preview videos, professional copywriting for descriptions

### **The PWA Alternative:**

The document mentions Progressive Web Apps (PWA) as an alternative:
- Users install directly from your website (bypasses stores entirely)
- **Pros**: No approval process, no store fees, instant updates, works on both platforms
- **Cons**: Less discoverable (not searchable in stores), less trusted by users, can't access all phone features, harder to monetize

This is a good interim solution while waiting for store approval, or a backup if stores reject you.

### **Accessibility Matters:**

The checklist mentions WCAG 2.1 AA standards:
- **What it means**: Website Content Accessibility Guidelines—ensuring people with disabilities can use the app
- **Requirements**: Screen reader support, sufficient color contrast, keyboard navigation, captions for audio
- **Why it matters**: Both stores check this, and it's also a legal requirement in many countries (including Australia)

### **The Review is Not Pass/Fail:**

Many people fear rejection, but it's actually a dialogue:
- **Rejections include specific feedback**: "Add Sign in with Apple," "Privacy policy link broken," etc.
- **You can fix and resubmit**: Review usually restarts within 24 hours
- **You can appeal**: If you disagree with a rejection, both stores have appeal processes
- **Reviewers want you to succeed**: They're not adversarial—they enforce policies to protect users

